AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:55.690
PROFESSOR: Clear for you.

00:45:55.690 --> 00:45:58.170
Any speculation on why
that would be true?

00:46:02.204 --> 00:46:03.120
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:12.974 --> 00:46:14.640
PROFESSOR: OK, what
we're saying is then

00:46:14.640 --> 00:46:27.570
that this is the left
ear for the low frequency

00:46:27.570 --> 00:46:30.355
and the right ear is, what?

00:46:30.355 --> 00:46:31.390
45 degrees?

00:46:31.390 --> 00:46:33.616
So it's going to be
sort of like this.

00:46:43.460 --> 00:46:45.515
OK, that's for maybe
the lower frequency.

00:46:46.990 --> 00:46:52.270
And the higher frequency is
quite a bit higher, right?

00:46:54.930 --> 00:46:59.000
It's more than
twice the frequency.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:00.850
So it's more than twice as much.

00:47:00.850 --> 00:47:03.600
I'm a terrible
artist, but it's going

00:47:03.600 --> 00:47:05.765
to go back and forth faster.

00:47:10.340 --> 00:47:15.790
And this is going to
be delayed 45 degrees.

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:19.080
So because this is
going faster, it's

00:47:19.080 --> 00:47:26.865
a smaller time difference
for the high frequency.

00:47:27.920 --> 00:47:31.630
So you might say, OK, it's
just a smaller time difference.

00:47:31.630 --> 00:47:34.350
And that's why it's harder
for us to distinguish it.

00:47:34.350 --> 00:47:37.070
But remember the concept
that we had of phase

00:47:37.070 --> 00:47:39.420
locking of the auditory nerve.

00:47:39.420 --> 00:47:43.280
In the auditory nerve,
the left auditory nerve

00:47:43.280 --> 00:47:45.961
is going to fire some spikes
at some point in the stimulus

00:47:45.961 --> 00:47:46.460
waveform.

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:49.280
The right auditory
nerve is going

00:47:49.280 --> 00:47:52.430
to fire some spikes at
a corresponding point

00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:55.470
in the stimulus waveform
for the first cycle.

00:47:55.470 --> 00:47:57.810
OK, let's repeat it
for the second cycle.

00:47:57.810 --> 00:47:59.362
Going to fire in
there somewhere.

00:47:59.362 --> 00:48:01.195
This one's going to
fire in there somewhere.

00:48:02.310 --> 00:48:04.940
And remember, cycles are
going by pretty quickly.

00:48:04.940 --> 00:48:06.530
There's lots of time.

00:48:06.530 --> 00:48:09.380
So you can build up
a response pattern

00:48:09.380 --> 00:48:12.010
where you have
thousands of spikes

00:48:12.010 --> 00:48:14.850
there, thousands of spikes here.

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:20.450
And these two auditory nerves
are coming into the brain.

00:48:20.450 --> 00:48:23.650
They're synapsing in the left
and right cochlear nucleus.

00:48:23.650 --> 00:48:25.180
Cochlear nuclei.

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:29.110
The cochlear nuclei are
then projecting centrally.

00:48:29.110 --> 00:48:32.911
And at some places, the left
and the right-side pathways

00:48:32.911 --> 00:48:33.410
converge.

00:48:35.090 --> 00:48:38.540
There's a comparator then that's
comparing the arrival time

00:48:38.540 --> 00:48:41.070
and it's saying the left ear
signal is getting to me first

00:48:41.070 --> 00:48:42.820
and the right ear is
a little bit delayed.

00:48:44.680 --> 00:48:46.760
What happens with
the higher frequency?

00:48:46.760 --> 00:48:48.700
So this is an interesting
high frequency.

00:48:48.700 --> 00:48:51.570
This is the 2,000 Hertz.

00:48:51.570 --> 00:48:53.500
What happens to
the phase locking

00:48:53.500 --> 00:48:57.120
for frequencies
above 1,000 Hertz?

00:48:57.120 --> 00:48:59.330
It declines, right?

00:48:59.330 --> 00:49:02.660
So instead of a nice
synchronized pattern,

00:49:02.660 --> 00:49:05.525
this left auditory nerve
is going to respond.

00:49:05.525 --> 00:49:06.800
The right is going to respond.

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:12.060
But from successive
cycle to cycle,

00:49:12.060 --> 00:49:14.660
the pattern is not
going to be synced

00:49:14.660 --> 00:49:17.515
to a particular point in
the stimulus waveform.

00:49:18.640 --> 00:49:24.627
So instead of getting a
nice synchronized pattern,

00:49:24.627 --> 00:49:25.960
it's going to be unsynchronized.

00:49:27.300 --> 00:49:29.530
And maybe for some
stimulus presentations,

00:49:29.530 --> 00:49:31.450
the right-side spike
is going to come

00:49:31.450 --> 00:49:33.480
in earlier than the left side.

00:49:33.480 --> 00:49:37.260
And the comparator
is going to say, WTF.

00:49:37.260 --> 00:49:39.965
I don't know where the
sound is coming from, right?

00:49:41.170 --> 00:49:44.560
So the fact that phase
locking breaks down

00:49:44.560 --> 00:49:48.100
means that the timing at
wherever the central comparator

00:49:48.100 --> 00:49:50.662
is, it's not synchronized.

00:49:53.020 --> 00:49:54.320
Timing here is synchronized.

00:49:54.320 --> 00:49:56.430
The timing here is
not synchronized.

00:49:56.430 --> 00:50:02.510
And we're claiming with
this psychophysical metrics

00:50:02.510 --> 00:50:06.160
that we can detect a
difference between the left

00:50:06.160 --> 00:50:09.133
and the right ear minimally
at 10 microseconds.

00:50:12.790 --> 00:50:14.980
With synchronized
patterns at least.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:19.930
Now, let me just draw--
it's not too surprised.

00:50:19.930 --> 00:50:23.490
Everybody understands why when
you break down phase locking,

00:50:23.490 --> 00:50:25.855
you don't have a
temporal code anymore?

00:50:27.940 --> 00:50:35.540
Let me show you the spike
waveforms for one spike coming

00:50:35.540 --> 00:50:36.920
in in the left
side and one spike

00:50:36.920 --> 00:50:40.700
coming in the right
side that are delayed

00:50:40.700 --> 00:50:42.930
by this minimal time
of 10 microseconds.

00:50:45.310 --> 00:50:50.890
So here is spike, let's
say the left side.

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:58.300
So to draw a spike coming in
from the right side delayed

00:50:58.300 --> 00:51:02.330
10 microseconds, I need to
know the time base here.

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:08.170
How long does it
take a spike to fire

00:51:08.170 --> 00:51:09.500
in the central nervous system?

00:51:09.500 --> 00:51:10.700
What is the duration here?

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:12.280
What's the time scale here?

00:51:12.280 --> 00:51:13.570
AUDIENCE: 1 millisecond.

00:51:13.570 --> 00:51:15.190
PROFESSOR: 1
millisecond, very good.

00:51:16.840 --> 00:51:20.840
OK, so now I'm going to draw
a right-side spike coming

00:51:20.840 --> 00:51:22.765
in that's delayed
by 10 microseconds.

00:51:22.765 --> 00:51:24.170
And it's pretty easy to do.

00:51:24.170 --> 00:51:26.500
I'm going to do it
in a different color,

00:51:26.500 --> 00:51:29.940
but it overlays
here very clearly.

00:51:29.940 --> 00:51:32.675
I didn't draw anything because
on this time [? base, ?]

00:51:32.675 --> 00:51:35.036
they're almost perceptually
indistinguishable.

00:51:39.180 --> 00:51:49.730
OK, so the right side here
delayed 10 microseconds.

00:51:49.730 --> 00:51:53.490
That's the wonderful
property of this system

00:51:53.490 --> 00:51:59.100
that we have relatively
large, long inputs coming

00:51:59.100 --> 00:51:59.865
into the CNS.

00:52:01.200 --> 00:52:04.570
And we can, at the
limits of our perception,

00:52:04.570 --> 00:52:08.570
distinguish delays of
a very short time scale

00:52:08.570 --> 00:52:10.420
on the order of 10 microseconds.

00:52:10.420 --> 00:52:14.460
That's the impressive nature
of this central comparator,

00:52:14.460 --> 00:52:15.530
wherever it is.

00:52:15.530 --> 00:52:19.880
And we're about to talk
about where it is now.

00:52:19.880 --> 00:52:27.280
So let's look at where
it is in the brain.

00:52:31.250 --> 00:52:34.730
We had our block diagram of
the central auditory pathway

00:52:34.730 --> 00:52:36.010
before.

00:52:36.010 --> 00:52:38.165
And here's kind of a
simplified diagram.

00:52:39.270 --> 00:52:41.270
This is the left side
and the right side

00:52:41.270 --> 00:52:44.650
of the brainstem with the
two auditory nerves coming

00:52:44.650 --> 00:52:46.410
into the two cochlear nuclei.

00:52:47.570 --> 00:52:49.510
And in the cochlear
nuclei, we discussed

00:52:49.510 --> 00:52:52.060
that the auditory nerve
synapses and cochlear

00:52:52.060 --> 00:52:55.530
nucleus neurons then
pick up the message.

00:52:55.530 --> 00:52:58.060
Now, in one sense the
cochlear nucleus neurons

00:52:58.060 --> 00:53:02.645
know only about what's going
on on that side of the brain,

00:53:02.645 --> 00:53:04.820
or that auditory nerve.

00:53:04.820 --> 00:53:07.500
They're not getting inputs
from the other side.

00:53:07.500 --> 00:53:10.580
So they're not
binaural, if you will.

00:53:10.580 --> 00:53:15.040
The first places where
you have binaural input

00:53:15.040 --> 00:53:17.190
in the auditory
pathway are centers

00:53:17.190 --> 00:53:20.380
like the superior
olivary complex.

00:53:20.380 --> 00:53:32.110
And we talked about that before,
Superior Olivary Complex,

00:53:32.110 --> 00:53:37.180
or SOC, having a bunch of
not only binaural inputs

00:53:37.180 --> 00:53:39.700
but a bunch of
different sub-nuclei.

00:53:39.700 --> 00:53:41.790
That's why it's
called a complex.

00:53:41.790 --> 00:53:44.110
One of the most important
of those sub-nuclei

00:53:44.110 --> 00:53:48.120
is the Medial Superior
Olive indicated here by MSO.

00:53:49.190 --> 00:53:53.680
And the MSO gets input from
the left cochlear nucleus

00:53:53.680 --> 00:53:55.080
if it's the left MSO.

00:53:55.080 --> 00:53:58.135
And it also gets input from
the right cochlear nucleus.

00:53:59.260 --> 00:54:04.130
And here is a very
good guess, at least,

00:54:04.130 --> 00:54:07.680
for where the
central comparator is

00:54:07.680 --> 00:54:10.260
on the basis of interaural
time differences.

00:54:11.690 --> 00:54:15.360
And this was appreciated
from very early time point.

00:54:15.360 --> 00:54:18.870
If you draw MSO neurons here,
they have two dendrites.

00:54:20.270 --> 00:54:22.770
One's going to the left side,
one's going to the right side.

00:54:22.770 --> 00:54:26.760
And they get numerous synaptic
inputs onto each dendrite.

00:54:27.810 --> 00:54:31.900
If you make a lesion, so you
interrupt the inputs coming

00:54:31.900 --> 00:54:35.960
from, for example, the
right side, all the inputs

00:54:35.960 --> 00:54:38.440
onto the right
dendrites drop off.

00:54:38.440 --> 00:54:40.000
So it looks like
all these inputs

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:41.370
are coming from the right side.

00:54:42.660 --> 00:54:45.470
They've dropped off when
their pathway has been cut.

00:54:45.470 --> 00:54:48.335
And the left ones remain
because their pathway is intact.

00:54:49.750 --> 00:54:53.550
So clearly, the MSO neurons
get input from the two sides.

00:54:54.702 --> 00:55:00.840
Now, way back in the
1940s, a psychologist

00:55:00.840 --> 00:55:05.090
whose name was Lloyd
Jeffress proposed the model

00:55:05.090 --> 00:55:07.020
for detection of the ITDs.

00:55:08.510 --> 00:55:13.490
And he guessed at several
locations in the brain

00:55:13.490 --> 00:55:16.330
where this model could
actually be present.

00:55:16.330 --> 00:55:19.250
And one of his guesses
was in the MSO.

00:55:19.250 --> 00:55:23.030
And it turns out the MSO was the
correct of his several guesses.

00:55:24.510 --> 00:55:28.490
And this is a very
interesting model

00:55:28.490 --> 00:55:30.930
for neural processing of ITDs.

00:55:32.240 --> 00:55:35.080
And it has several
important assumptions.

00:55:37.160 --> 00:55:41.310
First, the MSO receives
input from the left

00:55:41.310 --> 00:55:43.450
and the right side, as
we have just gone over.

00:55:45.510 --> 00:55:48.480
So these are axons coming
in from the left side.

00:55:48.480 --> 00:55:50.900
And these are axons coming
in from the right side.

00:55:50.900 --> 00:55:54.270
And the dots there are the
MSO neurons themselves.

00:55:56.850 --> 00:56:01.350
The dots are very
fussy kind of neurons.

00:56:01.350 --> 00:56:03.335
They don't just
respond to any input.

00:56:04.600 --> 00:56:06.150
They're very discerning.

00:56:06.150 --> 00:56:08.920
They say, OK, I got some
input from the left side.

00:56:10.100 --> 00:56:11.640
Not a big deal.

00:56:11.640 --> 00:56:14.960
We get some input
from the right side,

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:17.020
I'm not going to get
excited about that.

00:56:17.020 --> 00:56:20.330
But I'm going to get very
excited if I get input

00:56:20.330 --> 00:56:24.625
from the left and the right
side at the same time.

00:56:26.107 --> 00:56:27.106
That is, coincidentally.

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:31.870
And so the MSO
neurons are sometimes

00:56:31.870 --> 00:56:34.420
called coincidence detectors.

00:56:34.420 --> 00:56:37.570
That is, they detect
and they respond only

00:56:37.570 --> 00:56:41.080
when they get coincident
input from the left

00:56:41.080 --> 00:56:41.880
and the right side.

00:56:43.011 --> 00:56:44.450
Well, how's that
going to help us

00:56:44.450 --> 00:56:48.560
if we're delaying one
side versus the other?

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:52.140
Well, the second major
component of the Jeffress model

00:56:52.140 --> 00:56:55.730
is that the axons providing
input, which we now know

00:56:55.730 --> 00:56:58.550
are coming from the
cochlear nucleus,

00:56:58.550 --> 00:57:01.730
they run down the
length of the MSO.

00:57:01.730 --> 00:57:04.585
And as they run down the
length, they give off branches

00:57:04.585 --> 00:57:09.260
to each MSO neuron in this long
chain going from left to right.

00:57:10.910 --> 00:57:14.250
And if you know anything about
spikes that are traveling down

00:57:14.250 --> 00:57:18.260
axons or nerve
fibers, you'll know

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:20.550
that the spikes
don't get instantly

00:57:20.550 --> 00:57:23.400
to the very tip of the axon.

00:57:23.400 --> 00:57:26.840
But it takes them time
to travel down the axon.

00:57:26.840 --> 00:57:31.100
And so for example in this axon,
the impulse is coming down here

00:57:31.100 --> 00:57:33.790
and it gets to this
leftmost branch first.

00:57:35.130 --> 00:57:36.980
And then a little
bit later in time,

00:57:36.980 --> 00:57:38.230
it gets to the next branch.

00:57:39.330 --> 00:57:41.290
And so on and so
forth until it gets

00:57:41.290 --> 00:57:44.870
to the rightmost branch
at the longest delay.

00:57:46.560 --> 00:57:50.570
So Jeffress said, the inputs
to the MSO are, if you will,

00:57:50.570 --> 00:57:51.636
delay lines.

00:57:53.310 --> 00:57:58.340
That is, axonal impulse
propagation takes time.

00:57:58.340 --> 00:58:01.400
You can set these lines up
so that they are delay lines.

00:58:02.950 --> 00:58:05.825
The inputs on the right
have corresponding delays.

00:58:08.980 --> 00:58:10.676
Now, how big are the delays?

00:58:13.390 --> 00:58:15.210
And the flip side
of that question

00:58:15.210 --> 00:58:21.894
is, how long does it take
impulses to travel down axons?

00:58:24.535 --> 00:58:36.930
So another name for that is the
conduction velocity in axons.

00:58:36.930 --> 00:58:39.130
Well, these are,
let's say, myelinated

00:58:39.130 --> 00:58:43.430
axons of pretty big
size, like 5 micrometers.

00:58:44.600 --> 00:58:51.110
So let's say they're
myelinated, a large diameter.

00:58:55.800 --> 00:58:57.910
5 micrometers, let's say.

00:58:59.470 --> 00:59:02.560
It turns out that such
a conduction velocity

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:05.700
for those kinds of axons is
about 10 meters per second.

00:59:08.850 --> 00:59:11.430
And Jeffress was
sharp enough to know

00:59:11.430 --> 00:59:15.430
that in the dimensions
of the brain,

00:59:15.430 --> 00:59:17.640
those conduction
velocities work out

00:59:17.640 --> 00:59:20.460
to predict about the
right delay for the kinds

00:59:20.460 --> 00:59:22.660
of interaural time
differences that we're

00:59:22.660 --> 00:59:26.920
talking about for sounds
that differ in azimuth.

00:59:27.990 --> 00:59:32.350
So Jeffress, at the time he
was postulating his model

00:59:32.350 --> 00:59:35.150
in the 1940s, there
were good measurements

00:59:35.150 --> 00:59:36.935
of axonal conduction velocity.

00:59:37.990 --> 00:59:40.700
And he realized that
these delay lines

00:59:40.700 --> 00:59:45.210
were pretty good for
predicting or compensating

00:59:45.210 --> 00:59:46.715
for the interaural
time differences.

00:59:47.950 --> 00:59:49.300
Now, how does this model work?

00:59:49.300 --> 00:59:53.340
Well, I have a little demo of
the model, which is a movie.

00:59:56.025 --> 00:59:58.490
Which I have in a
different PowerPoint.

00:59:58.490 --> 01:00:03.815
And I'm going to show
this coincidence model.

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:12.450
And I guess I didn't
credit the person who

01:00:12.450 --> 01:00:15.749
made this movie,
which is Tom Yin.

01:00:20.137 --> 01:00:21.720
And he works on the
auditory brainstem

01:00:21.720 --> 01:00:24.094
and he's based at the University
of Wisconsin in Madison.

01:00:24.880 --> 01:00:28.400
So what this demo will
show you is you'll

01:00:28.400 --> 01:00:30.280
be looking down
onto the brainstem.

01:00:31.320 --> 01:00:35.550
And the MSO on the left side and
the right side will be present.

01:00:35.550 --> 01:00:39.710
The model is set up to demo
the MSO on the right side.

01:00:39.710 --> 01:00:42.440
There will be a
cochlea on the left

01:00:42.440 --> 01:00:44.620
and a cochlea on the right.

01:00:44.620 --> 01:00:46.950
The auditory nerve coming
into the cochlear nucleus

01:00:46.950 --> 01:00:48.890
on the left and
the auditory nerve

01:00:48.890 --> 01:00:51.260
coming into the cochlear
nucleus on the right.

01:00:51.260 --> 01:00:55.100
And those two nuclei will be
providing inputs to the MSO.

01:00:55.100 --> 01:00:58.030
And action potentials,
or impulses, along

01:00:58.030 --> 01:01:01.170
these nerve fibers
will be indicated

01:01:01.170 --> 01:01:03.530
by little highlights--
little yellow lights.

01:01:04.800 --> 01:01:08.410
And the demonstration
will show you

01:01:08.410 --> 01:01:11.980
what happens to these
incoming impulses that

01:01:11.980 --> 01:01:16.879
converge at the MSO for a
sound that's straight ahead.

01:01:16.879 --> 01:01:18.420
So a sound that's
straight ahead will

01:01:18.420 --> 01:01:21.040
strike the two
sides at the same--

01:01:21.040 --> 01:01:23.220
will strike the two
pathways at the same.

01:01:23.220 --> 01:01:26.055
And you'll see what
happens to the MSO

01:01:26.055 --> 01:01:29.090
and which neuron in the
coincidence detector

01:01:29.090 --> 01:01:31.050
array lights up.

01:01:31.050 --> 01:01:33.775
Then, I think it'll play that
same demo in slow motion.

01:01:35.240 --> 01:01:38.110
Then, the second part
of the demo I think

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:42.440
has the sound source displaced
off to the left side.

01:01:42.440 --> 01:01:46.160
So the sound wave front will
come and strike the left side

01:01:46.160 --> 01:01:49.520
first and the right
side after a delay--

01:01:49.520 --> 01:01:51.550
the interaural time difference.

01:01:51.550 --> 01:01:55.260
And you'll see what happens
to the impulses and the MSO

01:01:55.260 --> 01:01:59.645
neurons with that second
sound source position.

01:02:00.830 --> 01:02:06.670
So here are the two
cochleas, left and right.

01:02:06.670 --> 01:02:07.580
Here is the MSO.

01:02:11.350 --> 01:02:14.305
This is the right
cochlear nucleus.

01:02:14.305 --> 01:02:16.070
This is the left
cochlear nucleus.

01:02:17.280 --> 01:02:19.270
This is the MSO we're
not talking about.

01:02:19.270 --> 01:02:21.120
This is the right MSO.

01:02:21.120 --> 01:02:24.240
There was a sound wavefront
that hit the two sides equally.

01:02:24.240 --> 01:02:26.250
And it was a little
hard to appreciate,

01:02:26.250 --> 01:02:32.140
